# Logos

A logo is a visual representation of a brand or app (product). It can be a word or an image, or a combination of both.

![Banner for Logos page](/static/hero.light-d474fc9596d8f363645ef7a71e9919c95ef1c76ab554979f4b75ab1c59699a79.png)

## Download logos

The full set of app (product) logos are available in [Atlassian Mosaic](https://orangedam.atlassian.com/)

This page includes downloadable logo files for use in marketing contexts as well as specific usage
guidance for app or marketing contexts.

If you want to add logos to app (product) experiences, use the
[logo component](https://atlassian.design/components/logo/examples).

## Download the logos

Each downloadable file includes variations of color and layout in approved formats and the below
elements combined together:

- logomarks – the icon portion of a logo
- wordmarks – the name of the app (product) or property
- straplines or other secondary text.

Assets for isolated logomarks are also included.

![Annotated graphic of the Atlassian logo, showing the logomark, strapline and wordmark.](/b519cd5d849cb4afae973d67f588c89b/logo-anatomy.png)

### Our iconic Atlassian logo

Our iconic company logo.

Include `Atlassian` as the alt-text for the logo in digital experiences.

#### Atlassian app strapline

The Atlassian logomark and wordmark can be coupled with a list of app (product) names under it.
Follow the below guidance when using logos that contain straplines:

- Always centre the app names under the logo and don’t scale the logo below 280px wide.
- Write Atlassian and the app name in the alt-text in digital experiences.

![Logo strapline with Jira, Confluence, Trello and Bitbucket wordmarks center-aligned beneath the Atlassian logo.](/21f597d1f31e99180e9ccf2e82b47ac0/logo-centered.png)

### Attribution logos

The attribution logos are a type of lockup that combine app (product) or property logomarks with the
Atlassian strapline.

They create consistency in our portfolio, and help customers connect them with our overall Atlassian
brand. Follow the below guidance when using attribution logos:

- Only use attribution logos when the Atlassian context is not clear. For example, in
  advertisements, videos, and white papers. You don’t need to use them on Atlassian properties like
  [www.atlassian.com](https://www.atlassian.com) or in app (product) user interfaces.
- Never compose your own attribution logos or deconstruct the official assets.
- Write the name of the app (product)/property and Atlassian in the alt-text for in digital
  experiences.

### Property logos

The Atlassian program and property logos are a lockup of the Atlassian logomark and wordmark and the
name in Charlie Sans. Follow the below guidance when using property logos:

- On a white background, the program name is rendered in neutral with the logo in primary blue. On
  darker backgrounds, both program and logo are white.
- Write `Atlassian` and the name of the property as the alt-text in digital experiences.

### App (product) logos

With the Atlassian System of Work and collections framework our primary products, secondary products
and plaftform features are now referred to as apps.

We’ve updated our logos to reflect this change, using marks that symbolize functionality, contained
in a tile. An app’s glyph is chosen based on the apps functionality; its tile color refers to its
collection.

The logomarks are contained by a tile shape, colored with their associated collection. Follow the
below guidance when using App (product) logos:

- Use when the Atlassian context is clear.
- If you need to connect the app to Atlassian, use an attribution logo instead. For example, in a
  video or advertisement.
- Write the name of the apps in the alt-text in digital experiences.

Assets include both isolated logomarks and lockups with wordmarks.

#### Logomarks

A logomark is a symbol or icon shown without the app (product)/property name or brand workmark. For
an app (product), this refers to the tile. Follow the below guidance when using logomarks:

- If you’re including the logomark in product experiences, use the
  [icon](https://atlassian.design/components/logo/examples#icon) variant of the logo component.
- Only use logomarks on their own when the context is very clear and where possible pair with
  descriptive text.
- Write `Atlassian` or the app/property name in the alt-text in digital experiences.

![](/ba197dea244be4b5c7843e333393d74e/lockups-nav.png)

Logomarks are paired with native text in top navigations.

![](/cc067a8489ddf25d2be23a8a28d07366/logos-contained-logomarks.png)

Logomarks are suitable when rendering the app name natively in its environment is more legible and
user-friendly.

![](/8839ec73382c05d396bb84f5b9ca3a7a/logos-jira-app-store.png)

Logomarks can be used when environmental restrictions do not allow for proper clearance guidelines
to be followed for full logos.

#### Logomark shape and size

The [logo](https://atlassian.design/components/logo) component comes in specific sizes and the
logomark has a pre-defined radius. These should not be altered.

The exception to this is when appearing on external sources such as Apple mobile apps and Google
Marketplace where specific container shapes need to be used.

Logomarks should never be nested inside additional containers.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

#### Do

Use the default radius values that are applied to the backgrounds of app logo icons.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

#### Don’t

Don’t adjust the radius values of the backgrounds of product logo icons.

![](/static/containers-do-a34d012e35ec39dcae307e9d0853894c6f5f6d7c285f3d0e2c73e1f87a21f1f8.png)

#### Do

Allow breathing room around product logo icons.

![](/static/containers-dont-6ae4ac9f7198f041482e6aca977a8cd7a34d7d9f121442e100f79ac276991d64.png)

#### Don’t

Don’t add unnecessary containers around app logo icons.

### Aligning logos

#### Align logomarks with other elements

- Middle align with the logo mark when the copy is less than the height of the container.
- Top-align or stack below with center-alignment if it’s taller than the container.

![](/0704c25e22117032d15ad9fdd90fc512/logos-alignment-ratio.png)

#### Aligning app (product) logos

Where app (product) logos are arranged in a vertical or horizontal list, use the height or weight of
the logomark portion to align.

![](/c0d1dc1f25465ea192315925f8a2183c/tile-align-horizontal.png)

![](/236721f5dacf92a6ddbe8e80624247e8/tile-align-vertical.png)

## Logo clearance

When displaying logos outside of an app UI, surround them with clear space free of type, graphics,
and other elements that might cause visual clutter.

#### Ideal clearance — Atlassian logo

![](/8db9a3ddbe191a235fd7715accfd3554/clearance-horizontal.png)

![](/96d30339e91054c564544b8e4a5e55e3/clearance-vertical.png)

#### Minimum clearance — Atlassian logo

Use the capital "A" of the Atlassian wordmark to define the minimum clearance around the logo.

![](/dd243127110d94c43e54826e54fcc31f/top-bottom-clearance-atlassian.png)

#### Ideal clearance — app (product) logo

![](/05c86b7d00c8dca688bbf592c5458713/logos-ideal-clearance-app.png)

#### Minimum clearance — app (product) logo

Use the height and width of the logo wordmark to find the minimum clearance around the logo.

![](/41f64d55ae15ea4165e72bb1b5627391/top-bottom-clearance-app.png)

## Color options

Logos are available in three color options to suit different colored environments – Brand, inverse
and neutral.

![](/57d087176b2ec971d7133cd4778ed833/logo-stack-colors.png)

Don’t edit or place logos in ways that reduce the clarity and legibility of the image.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

#### Don’t

Don’t use unapproved color combinations.

![](/static/shadow-dont-1a588aa91242725d8c7290284a553e26de95914570fc96ee66660286845404f5.png)

#### Don’t

Don’t use a drop shadow.

![](/static/legibility-dont-7c059f88ce0baae4de0d5560f2f773182e234d51d569140cab9499849cba7ee2.png)

#### Don’t

Don’t use the logo on top of complex backgrounds.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

#### Don’t

Don’t outline the logo.
